creator: Pascual, Jean-Paul (informant), Ginouvès, Veronique (investigator), Siino, François (investigator)
description: French, Jean-Paul Pascual obtained his scholarship at the end of his studies in Arabic, history and anthropology, enabling him, in 1969, to continue his training at the IFEAD. The Institute, then under the direction of André Raymond, is a true crossroads for the scientific community, both Syrian and international. As a doctoral student, Jean-Paul Pascual finds a place in Damascus that is conducive to the pursuit of his study of language, but also a stimulating scientific environment that will help him redefine his own research activities and orient himself towards the study of archives. After a two-year stay and a military service where he also studied Arabic as a teacher and interpreter, in 1972 Jean-Paul Pascual obtained a post at the Beirut School of Course in sociology and history until 1975. At the outbreak of the war in Lebanon, he was recruited by IFEAD as scientific secretary, a position he held until 1987. With Sarab Atassi, to organize, in conjunction with the Syrian authorities, the project for the compilation of photographic and topographical documentation on Old Damascus. Although Pascual subsequently returned to France to pursue his research at Iremam (Aix-en-Provence), he continued to maintain regular relations with the IFEAD and, later, Ifpo Where he went several times to participate in archaeological excavations at various sites in the Near East. Not only in this interview will we find a rich account of the journey of a historian and Arabic scholar, Arabist, specialist in the Ottoman Near East, but also a valuable testimony on the evolution of the Institute from the late 1960s to the First decade of the 21st century. Indeed, his listening illuminates the internal organization of the Institute, the relations with society and the local scientific community and the role of the various directors over the years. Jean-Paul Pascual also mentions several times the political events which agitated Lebanon and Syria during his presence in the Middle East: the opportunity to recall that the research work is never carried out outside of any political context. Evocation of Schematic Index of Ta 'apos; rih Baghdad & apos; Ali Khaib al-Baghdadi. There are several references to Arabic words or phrases including the verb muzahara (manifest).
format: 2 digital file, Two digital files, cut into 5 files.

title: The evolution of the IFEAD since the late 1960s through the gaze of an historian and Arabic scholar

creator: Ginouvès, Veronique (investigator), Lentin, Jerome (informant)
description: Jérôme Lentin gives a testimony on the evolution of the Institute covering a period of almost forty years. He discovers the IFEAD and meets André Raymond in 1972 while studying Arabic at the CREA in Beirut. Holder of an Arabic aggregation, he obtained a post of pensioner at the IFEAD in 1976 and held the position of scientific librarian of the Institute from 1979 to 1984. While the IFEAD became Ifpo, Resides from 2008 to 2010 as a researcher in delegation to work on the project of a dictionary of dialect Arabic. The path of Jérôme Lentin gives him a privileged place to account for the different aspects of the evolution of the Damascus Institute. This interview, in spite of its mediocre sound quality, evokes the changes and reports of the staff of the Institute, the roles of the various directors (in terms of openness to Syrian society or organization of work), scientific orientations Or the different forms that the collection of archives could take during its presence. A specialist in dialectology, Jérôme Lentin also explains the difficulties he encountered in the practice of his discipline among the members of the scientific community and even towards a part of Syrian society. The interview concludes with suggestions from people who can be met for further investigation.

title: Testimony of the evolution of the French Institute of the Near East over four decades

creator: Picard, Jacques (informant), Ginouvès, Veronique (investigator), Siino, François (investigator)
description: Jacques Picard discovers the IFEAD as early as 1955, then under the responsibility of Nikita Elisséeff. At the time, he went to the Institute to learn Arabic. If he is to leave Damascus the following year because of the Suez Canal crisis, he will make regular visits from Lebanon in the early 1960s. While working in Cairo IFAO, he became friends with Thierry Bianquis; The latter will invite him to join the IFEAD from 1976 to work to publish the work of the Institute. Jacques Picard worked at the printing press and then became an active witness to the changeover to the computerization of the publishing department. From 1996 onwards, he served as Intendant of the Institute. Since his retirement in 2005, Jacques Picard regularly visits the Sahnaya depot to help with the replenishment of works. This interview provides a singular testimony for several reasons about the Institute: the age of Jacques Picard's relationship with The IFEAD offers a unique perspective on its history (in relation to changes in the country and changes in personnel). On the other hand, the witness brings a different point of view to that of the expatriate researcher, who makes him feel strongly the importance of the opening of the Institute to Syrian society and the major role of Syrian personnel, living memories of the Place., French

title: Working for editing at a French research institute in Damascus, from the 1950s to the 1990s

creator: Committee of Countries Asses, Verdon, Vaïre, Var (sponsor), White, Emile (informant), Cassé, Corinne (investigator)
description: A few names of tools are given in Provencal, French, Provencal, and the interview takes place in the town hall on a day of voting. We can hear the arrival of the voters. The informant born in 1933 in Argens evokes the beginning of the cultivation of lavender. He cites the Mane distillery in Saint-André-les-Alpes, La Mure, Thorame Haute, Thorame Basse, La Bâtie, and remembers the glorious years of lavender. It explains in detail the operation in cooperative of the distillery of the Mure. This is an opportunity for the informant to cite the evolution of hoeing, cutting and transport techniques as well as the status of the harvested areas and the timing permitting the cutting. It attests to the hiring of Italian and Spanish agricultural employees formerly for the cutting and the quantity of the grounds of lavender now covered with forest. Other information is given on the presence of wild or cultivated lavender fields, the role of traders in the 1936s, and the selling price in the 1950s. In describing the state of the roads at that time, the informant cited The lavender lands of the Mane family in Saint-André-les-Alpes. - 13:28 At the request of the interviewer the informant gives more details on the work of the brokers and price changes involving the complementarity of incomes such as mushroom picking. The discussion revolves around the details of her childhood life (lighting "with bold pine", oil, carbide, lighting with electricity in 1947, pedestrian movements, farm products). After citing commodity barter during the 1939 war, the informant remembers the school and his parents' crop and wheat crops, the work and tools of which he describes. - 41:15 The informant then tells of the preparation of the flour, the place of the mills and the making of the bread. There is also talk of planting new feet of lavender from the wild seeds. The testimony takes up the thread of the biography of the informant who quickly evokes the episode of the Algerian war, his work on the family farm, and then, in more detail, his work on cutting wood before he entered the bridges and roads. He cites his complementary activities (lavender, replacements in the post). Some details are given on the operation of the cooperative distillery of La Mure which distil up to 600 kilos of lavender by "boiled". The role of brokers is again discussed. -1: 13: 11 Finally, the informant attests to sheep grazing on lavender lands, comparing his work to that of his father. The son of the informant intervenes to remind the importance of the distillery of the Mure and the heating means used by the elders to exploit to the maximum the capacities of an alembic.

creator: Magendie, Edmond (informant), Suzzarini, Michel (investigator)
description: The inquiry opens with a vague questioning of the period 1930-1945 by the investigator. The informant says his testimony is not a mere testimony. He defined himself as a sort of janissary, a servant of the state, a mission transmitted by his father, a career officer. He studied at the institution of the Marists of La Seyne-sur-Mer, of which he is deeply grateful. Following a military school, he left the school of Saint-Cyr in 1933. The informant had to follow the path of his father in the military career. He describes the journey of his father who wanted his son to accomplish the same: "prolong my father, do what he would have done". When he left school he joined the colonial infantry. He considers the period 1930-1945 as a period of humiliation for the West. He is very admiring the men of the generation of his father who led the war of 1914-1918. Refusing the Armistice, he escaped from Djibouti in 1940 and joined the Allies in Aden, then the French Free Forces, of which he learned only then (radio stations having been confiscated in Djibouti). This position of rebel is then new in his life. He made a parallel with his political career at the Rally for France (elected deputy R.P.F. in Djibouti from 1951 to 1955). He remembers his state of consciousness at the time of his leaving Saint-Cyr. To illustrate the state of mind felt at that time, he said that as a lieutenant, he had proposed to literacy the conscripts, episode having attracted the sympathy of teachers hitherto antimilitarist. He discusses the neutrality of the army in his day. He feels at a time when he is talking about the lack of civic education and the lack of opinion. He returns to his experience of military disobedience, declaring that by taking up his profession he had pledged allegiance to France and not to the marshal. It tells of his departure, the moment of his decision, and the dilemma between an internal resistance and an external resistance. He repeats the account of his adhesion to the French Free Forces, where he says to find the true "dough" of the nation. He gives his vision of the defeat of 1940, makes a criticism of Gamelin. He praises the nuclear power. Regarding his case, he refuses to speak of heroism. He briefly recalled the landing at Cavalaire. The informant then makes general remarks about the lack of civility and courage, the loss of values. He returns to the importance of the values ​​inherited from his father. At the end of the interview, he returned to the job of the troop officer, on the necessity of the critical spirit by reporting the anecdote of a general having accepted that his division attacks in mountain without suitable equipment. The recording is stopped suddenly. The technique of the investigator is hesitant, it does not relaunch the informant whose speech is left free from beginning to end without request for further study. The testimony is largely an account of vocation., French
subject: Djibouti, inheritance, Franco-German Armistice of 1940, military career, La-Seyne-sur-Mer, Military, army, life story, Resistance, FFL, Petain, Philippe, father-child relationship, obedience, war of 1939-1945 , 1930s, patriotism, field recording
title: A soldier who joined the French Free Forces during the war of 1939-1945 traces his course and gives his vision of the army

creator: Barone, Nadège (investigator), Arnaud, Gabriel (informant)
description: French, Gabriel Arnaud is a retired farmer who has always lived in Auriol. At 62 years old at the time of the interview, he has been a member of the Saint Eloi group since 1987. He is very attached to the associative life that reigns around this festive event. It is as treasurer of the association that he is questioned by Nadège Barone, student in history, who writes a memorial on the feast of Saint Eloi in Auriol. He joined the group because the Saint Eloi celebrates the usefulness of the animals of traits, especially that of the horses, with which he worked all his life. Saint Eloi is also the saint of farriers, carters and laborers. Thanks to an inheritance and a certain experience, the informant defines himself as a link between the former celebration and that of today. His father was captain of the Saint Eloi in 1913, the last one to have been organized before 1984. It was him himself in 1994. His narrative highlights the historical aspects which have been reintroduced since: the role of the "gaillardet" , The definition of the "cavalcade", the place of women within the association or the solidarity existing between the different groups of the villages of Provence. The investigator places great emphasis on the masculinity of the Saint Eloi. His testimony tells us about the symbolism of this festival, its history and its importance in Auriol as well as in Provence, where it is celebrated from every side.
subject: Romevaire, group of the Saint Eloi of Auriol, aubade, the Cavalcade, chariot of feast, revivalism, summer, festivity of trade, testimony Thematic, field recording, ritual object of the festival, Auriol, saint Eloi, rivalry village
title: Testimony of an active member of the Saint Eloi group in Auriol in Provence in the late 1990s

creator: Father, Bertochi (informant), Barone, Nadège (investigator)
description: French, Nadège Barone, a student studying history, is studying the religious aspect of this Provençal feast as part of her oral investigations on the Feast of Saint Eloi in Auriol. Father Bertochi, is at the time of the interview, rector of Notre Dame de la Garde in Marseille. He was pastor of Auriol until 1993. With a few years of retreat, he gives a rather critical testimony on the organization of the Saint Eloi. The informant expresses himself with a certain caution that loosens over the interview. According to him, the sacred elements that are part of the Saint Eloi are maintained only to elaborate a folkloric atmosphere, they are components that belong to the past, which fall into disuse. The Saint Eloi is a reactivation of the past, the organizers integrate the religious in the same way that they encourage the Provencal culture according to the informant. He would like to place the religious in the heart of the Saint Eloi so that it does not distort itself further. He admits that it must correspond to a new public, which no longer places faith as the central element of his life, but denounces an invasion of folklore which he considers "bad" for this event. For example, he never succeeded in obtaining silence during the mass on Sunday morning of Saint Eloi. He likens this vision of Provence to comedy. He regretted that the Saint Eloi now belonged to the associations, and no longer to the workers of the land, to the inhabitants of Auriol themselves. It would no longer symbolize these rural trades but only the draft animals, mainly the horse. The informant deplores that the parish priest is not part of the decision-makers and that only his function is exploited.
subject: Horse, Auriol, Saint Eloi, Mass, Saint Eloi group of Auriol, revivalism, faith, thematic testimony, field recording, folklorization of tradition, preservation of traditions, evolution of religious practices, Notre-Dame- Guard, religious identity, votive festival, blessing of the flock, religious doctrine, transmission of religion, summer, craft
title: Personal considerations of the rector of our Lady of the Guard, former parish priest of Auriol until the early 1990s, on the feast of Saint Eloi

creator: Béchard, Marjorie (Investigator), Multiple (informant)
description: Fre, Student in Master 2 History in the Telemme laboratory, Marjorie Béchard is interested in the social uses of history through the medieval feast of Saint Louis de Aigues-Mortes. In 2008, the interviewer gathered the testimony of 30 minutes of one of the creators of the party and then, during the three days of festivity of 2009, she carried out 15 investigations, about 2h 30min of recording, interrogating in situ several Actors of various fields: craftsmen, amateurs of historical reconstruction, members of various associations. She also recorded two re-enactments of medieval marriage and dubbing.
subject: Academic learning, history, thematic testimony, field recording, soundscape
title: Social uses of history through the medieval festival of Aigues-Mortes

At the same time questions arise concerning the choice and posture of witnesses and the different levels of discourse in the same testimony (biographical narrative, requests for knowledge, etc.)

description: French, The testimony depends on the interaction with the investigator, the modalities of the exchange, and the sharing of the speech. For the analysis of the interview, it is necessary to highlight the conditions of production of the utterance, the context in which the speech occurs. This intervention is followed by a debate on the question of the legitimacy of the research from the point of view of observed observation. Is not the informant ultimately the & quot; co-author & quot; The research?

creator: February, Cécile (investigator), Coco de Samatan (informant), Compagnie du Lamparo (author legal entity)
description: For the sake of the investigator, the informant tries to use correct French throughout the interview. The informant explicates several expressions, including: & apos; & apos; Go to Endoume & apos ;, apos; & apos; & apos; Ask to Belsunce & apos; & apos; (Which means to ask for money from Belsunce & apos ;, in connection with the statue of Monsignor Belsunce in front of the Cathedral of Marseilles represented with both arms open, seeming to mean that he can do nothing for The applicant). Through this testimony are delimited the borders of the small neighborhood of Samatan, up from Endoume. It describes an identity specific to its inhabitants, people often very poor at the time of the childhood of the informant. The latter is not very old (about 60 years old at the time of the interview) but he remembers many stories and anecdotes that were told by the elders in the evening along the sidewalks. Surprising characters and narratives populate the testimony: werewolves, singers, headless women, mysterious tunnels ... The relations between the neighboring districts, those of the Vallon des Auffes, those of the Catalans, and the surrounding parks and pine forests ., Regional French

creator: Vives (author legal person), Abrahamian, Mooshegh (informant), Gaucher, Anne-Sylvie (investigator), AD 13 (sponsor)
description: Armenian, the informant sings a song in Armenian (track 2 of CD2) and translates it. He also sings the beginning of a Turkish song (track 3 of CD2). The informant tells the story of his ancestors at length. Throughout the interview, he constantly places it in a global historical context, giving then His vision of this past. Having carried out a great deal of historical research, he drew on his bases of understanding and found explanations as to the internal and external causes of Armenian misfortune (tendency to subjugation, pantanism, sociology). He is quite critical of historians, who, according to him, have not worked enough on the role of France in Anatolia between 1918 and 1922. He himself wrote a pamphlet, entitled & quot; All guilty ", expressing the results of his analyzes. He explains the course of his paternal grandfather, who died in 1918 in a battle, then his father: in exodus after the genocide, put in an orphanage, and then working at the opera of Yerevan in the 1930s (Of which he will bring back records still preserved by the informant). He married in Armenia, had a child, was engaged at the front during the second war and then taken prisoner in Germany. He entered a legion of the German army and came to Paris in 1948. The informant also tells the story of his mother. The informant succinctly recounts their life in the Cadet district, the Armenian quarter of the 9th arrondissement of Paris, where the preservation of culture within the community rubbed shoulders with the need for integration. His father having arrived later in France, he repeatedly expressed his chance to receive a good transmission of this culture. Especially the music, the songs (he sings two songs, one in Turkish and one in Armenian), and especially the language (which allowed him to translate recently Raffi's book "The Fool"). He speaks of the increasingly distant family relationships and the loss of language, which results from a process of assimilation, which does not favor relations with people of Armenian descent. He is proud of his identity (he feels Armenian), claims it and wishes to pass it on to his daughter. So he gave her an Armenian first name, taught her the language and made her aware of the collective story. After mentioning his belated rediscovery of this history and of this country, he speaks about his associative activism (SPFA), among others by means of donations and actions in favor of the recognition of the genocide. He often takes advantage of the promotion of his book, and newspaper articles, to uncover this story and go against " Discretion & quot; Armenian conflict which he calls into question several times. He recounts his various trips to Armenia in the 1990s and 2000s and analyzes the difficulties of the Armenian people in forming a nation. He expressed his concern about the current situation in the country: economically aided by the diaspora, marked by wars and corruption, threatened with loss of cultural identity and refusing to give Armenian citizenship to members of the diaspora. He finally motivated his testimony by the desire to leave an oral trace of this history, parallel to his writing activity., French, Turkish

creator: 1030 (informant), 1031 (informant), Paroles Vives (author legal entity), AD 13 (sponsor), Cassé, Corinne (investigator)
description: The first part of the interview is devoted to the life story of the husband. He details the course of his parents, arrived from Turkey in 1923 in Marseille, and specifies especially their living conditions once in France: lodging in camps in the district of Crottes after having been in a hotel Door of Aix, then installation In houses in La Cabucelle. He also mentions the poor reception made by the French until the 1940s, as well as the difficult relations with other foreign communities. The informant tells at length about the organization of everyday life in barracks, with the recomposition of a life & As at home & quot; (Pooling of money, mutual aid, marriages, school, religious ceremonies especially for Easter, learning the French language). He then details his professional career (sewing job, attempted emigration to the United States), and the difficult jobs his parents occupied (carpet salesman, bean sorter). He discusses the family transmission of the Armenian history, briefly describes his relationship with the Gregorian church, and talks about the ways of meetings between Armenian nationals (soccer teams constituted by regions of origin). The second part of the interview is devoted to the life story of his wife, whose parents lived in the center of Marseille before building a house in Olives. She describes the chaotic life course of her father (difficulties in finding work, participation in the Second World War), then tells her story (participation in an Armenian religious choir, work in a sewing factory, advantages and disadvantages of working House). The informant talks about the various relationships with the Armenian community through games or participation in the outings of the Valabre campaign. They then recount their meeting on the occasion of a ball of the football team, talk about the importance of endogamous marriage and evoke the place of the Armenian woman. They describe precisely the course of their marriage (costumes, meals, ceremony, choice of sponsors and godmothers, music and dances), as well as the unfolding of a baptism, comparing them with the French ceremonies. The couple reflects on the nature of their identity, is defined as & quot; Marseilles origin of Armenian origin ", and declines two typical characteristics of their culture of origin which are the sense of the hospitality and the kitchen (recipes of cooking). Finally, they talk about their connection with present-day Armenia (presence of family and friends who are staying there), and how they see this deposit: both an act of respect for their ancestors, and a possibility of transmitting This story to their grandchildren and & quot; Others ". The interview concludes with a divination session in the reading of the collector's coffee grounds, in Armenian, translated by the daughter of the informant. The latter then explains the procedure, which it can read, and expresses its doubts as to the transmission or not of this practice. The informants often insist on the suffering experienced during the first 20 years in France and then on the fact that the situation is clearly improved after the Second World War. It is a good testimony on life in the refugee camps, where a lot of information is given on intercommunity relations (especially with the Spaniards and the Greeks). Interesting passage of reading in coffee grounds as divinatory practice (track 5 of CD3)., French, Armenian

creator: Agopian, Jean-Marie (informant), AD 13 (sponsor), Paroles Vives (author legal entity), Amellal, Kristel (investigator)
description: French, In the first part of the interview, the informant describes what he knows about the history of his paternal grandparents, who arrived from Armenia in Marseilles in 1920. First settled in Saint-Antoine, then In Gardanne (where the grandfather worked at the mine during the day and at a baker's shop at night), he then tells the story of their life in the Beaumont district of Marseille. He talks about his father's educational background and the various trades he has practiced. The informant emphasizes that these grandparents never spoke of their life in Armenia, nor of the genocide, and that he understood their attitude " Worried & quot; (Especially in relation to children) by watching H. Verneuil's films. He continues to decline the life of his parents and tells the complications (for the French family of his mother) due to this mixed marriage. He recounts the monthly family reunions, apart from the religious gatherings (even if he was raised in the Catholic religion), marked by strong relations. He reflects on the values ​​transmitted by his father, on which he constantly returns, in particular honesty, uprightness and autonomy, while wondering if they are really typically Armenian. A discussion is then held on the differences between girls and boys in Armenian culture, as well as on the importance of the choice of given names given to children. Relations with family members, academic and professional background (master's degree in agro-food and in parallel management of a company) are also discussed. He admits that he knows little about Armenia, is not at all committed, and gives his opinion on the present country while noting that no member of his family has expressed the need or the desire to do so. to go back there. He explains that his family has never established too many ties with the Armenian community in the past, and speaks of the relations he has today with Armenian nationals in particular in the world of work (recognition by the surname And sharing identical values). Finally, he gives the reasons for this testimony, namely to keep track of his father's journey, and to help better understand the Armenian history.

creator: Paroles Vives (author body corporate), Gaucher, Anne-Sylvie (investigator), AD 13 (sponsor), Bardzakian, Jean-Claude (informant)
description: By relying on family archives (photographs, administrative papers, old records of traditional music) that have been brought back and preserved, the informant tells the story of his family history. This was transmitted to him by his grandmother (Armenian from Turkey, victim of the genocide), with whom he lived, who never spoke of this traumatic episode himself. He also tells of the life of his great-grandfather, trading with his brothers, settled in various countries of the world, and then executed in 1915. The informant then reads the precise written testimony about the period of the genocide, written by His father after the memories of the grandmother. He repeatedly speaks of the rejection of his origins on the part of his father (religion, social relations). Indeed, even if the Armenian culture was present (by spoken oriental languages, cooking, ways of living and family life combined), it was not asserted because of a very strong desire for integration . Similarly, in Marseille, Rue Caisserie, where they had a jewelery shop, they were not installed in Armenian neighborhoods (which did not prevent them from helping the community as a public writer). The informant also pointed out that the marriage of his father with a Frenchman was badly received. So there was little transmission of the Armenian culture, if it is not a family spirit, some dishes like the dolma, the beureks or the stuffed mussels of which it gives the recipe, the practice of the table game the talva where The figures are said in Persian and Turkish, and finally how to prepare the coffee). He experienced an interest in this culture at the age of 20, resulting in his father rediscovering his origins. The question of travel to Armenia is then discussed. It tells the moving journey made by her grandmother in Turkey in the 1970s in the footsteps of her past, her father's refusal to go there and her own desire to do so, but not in the form of one Organized tourist trip. Along with his wife, however, they admit that they are not very connected to members of the Armenian community or their families, even though they refer to relatives in England and the United States via the Internet . They are not involved in the voluntary sector, have little involvement in the activities, but read books and learn a little about Armenian news. After discussing his career (in social and heritage), the interview focuses on the transmission of this culture to their four children. This consists mainly of answering their questions and maintaining family memory, which is necessary to fight against oblivion and the lack of recognition of genocide. The informant, who feels " Internationalist ", gives his vision of this country to which he is sentimentally attached, and which represents the place of conservation of the Armenian language and heritage. He feared and noticed a loss of this culture, with the diaspora and with the generations. Finally, he thinks that his testimony, added to a multitude of others, will help the recognition of the genocide and of what his ancestors really lived., French

creator: 1059 (informant), Gaucher, Anne-Sylvie (investigator), AD 13 (sponsor), Paroles Vives (author legal entity)
description: Armenian, The informant has difficulty expressing herself in French. She reads a poem (track 2 of CD1), and a text by C. Aznavour (track 3 of CD1) in Armenian, The recording starts with an interview with the informant, Armenian arrived in Martigues for 4 years, Difficult to navigate because of his poor command of French. She explains the motives of her exile and that of her husband, mainly due to political reasons. However, their already large children remained in Armenia. She succumbs to the question of her naturalization and her daily life: weekly links with Armenian martial families, how she learns French, her practice of religion. She talks a bit about the story of her grandparents but can not speak French in the genocide. The informant quickly gave a few recipe names for traditional cuisine, recited two poems in Armenian, and listened to a small excerpt of Armenian music played by D. Gasparian. She then speaks with pleasure of her country, including Mount Ararat and Lake Sevan, and famous people. The second part of the interview is devoted to her husband, who in turn speaks of his journey: born in Yerevan, engaged in the Armenian police in 1989 until 1998, and then entered the political party opposition, he Suffered a repression obliging him to leave. He gives his vision of France (a country he considers as "near" to Armenia), and highlights, on numerous occasions, respect for this country and for certain French historical political figures. He tells his family story, transmitted by his grandmother (grandparents who were victims of the genocide in Turkey, left in Greece, then returned to Armenia in 1947), then gives a long opinion on Armenia today, in particular in terms of regime policy. He said his refusal to keep abreast of Armenian news is that the media are false and do not reflect the difficult conditions of life. He also expresses his opinion on the film of R. Guediguian which shows only against the bad sides of this country. The attachment to his culture remains strong and he wants to preserve his identity. What he implements in the importance given to religion (regular Catholic practice, participation in baptisms and marriages, ceremonies carried out in the same way in Armenia), in the use of the Armenian language, in the maintenance of the Family memory, listening to traditional music and cooking. This is possible only within an Armenian community. Lastly, he refers to the notion of respect for the country of welcome and integration, evoking his difference of opinion with an African immigrant friend. What he reaffirms at the time of his motivation to deposit this testimony: desire to say that one must preserve his culture while respecting France., French

creator: Unknown (informant), Miller, Catherine (investigator)
description: Recorded an interview with Abdel Rahman Sule, an 80-year old bari Muslim, formerly president of the Malekkiyya (Garawiyya) court. The old man tells the story of the city of Juba and relates the modern history of Sudan during the Turkiyya period (linked to the Egyptian occupation of the second half of the 19th century and to the Mahdiyyah). Abdel Rahman Sule also refers to Belgian colonization (in the Congo), then British and traces the history of Sudan to the present day (1980s). He ended his testimony by mentioning the exercise of justice in this part of the country. The second part of the survey reveals some anecdotes about Abel Rahman Sule's personal journey, including his conversion to Islam and his learning of the Arabic language. The juba-arabic used by Abdel Rahman Sule is the one that is Spoken by elders over 50 years old., Juba-arabic

description: French, the informant was elected Secretary of the Supervisory Board of Miramas SNCF Maintenance, at the time of its merger with the SNCF workshops in Arles. She worked in the administration of the Arles workshops and was very impressed by the size of the buildings and the workforce. It witnessed their closure in 1984 and 1985, against which it fought with the railwaymen of Arles and Miramas. She explains her union involvement, her role as secretary to CE, her understanding and her connections with the community, especially about the workshops of Arles and their need for recognition. She cites the reasons why people go back to the SNCF like the notoriety of the company and the social achievements. It notes a strong sense of identity of the railwaymen of the workshops of Arles because of their number but also their common struggles and their know-how. She expresses her feeling about the rehabilitation of the workshops of Arles in cultural space and place of memory railroad and its own attachment. It details the evolution of the place of women within the SNCF.

creator: Amellal, Kristel (Investigator), Museon Arlaten (Sponsor), 1125 (informant)
description: This is the second interview with the informant. He tells his life as a railwayman through photographs that he had taken. Syndicated and engaged politically, he often had problems with his hierarchical superiors, notably for his demands and the strikes that he made against the closure of the SNCF workshops in Arles. He talks about the rivalries that existed between strikers and non-strikers, that he calls "foxes". He details his professional career and explains that he enjoyed his job as a coiler electrician and explains some aspects of it. Worker in the mechanical section of the workshops of Arles, the informant was in contact with dangerous products and was subject to a special medical follow-up every 6 months. He explains that he did not really appreciate the spirit of the railwayman and that he was afraid of his colleagues working outside the workshops. The informant talks about his extra-professional activities that were essentially focused on his trade union involvement., Français

creator: LASMIC (author legal entity), AD06 (author legal entity), Bottaro, Alain (investigator), Gastaldi, Armand (informant), Klingbeil, Emmanuel (investigator), MSH Nice
description: The informer, whose family (Italian) is a native of Free for a long time, was born in 1931. It testifies about some anecdotes occurred in Free and in the maquis during the years 1940. With the attachment of Breil-on-Roya To France in 1947, the hamlet of Libre became French without a referendum. In the same year, the informant volunteered as a volunteer with the French paratroopers for a period of 5 years during which he served for the French army in Indo-China, North Africa and Germany. Communicating at the time only in libraries, the informant learns French from the army. Nationalized French belatedly (1975), he reproached France for not having taken into account his services to the army. His wife intervenes several times during the interview and the couple do not agree on the relations between the villagers of Libre and Breil. The informant continued his testimony by referring to various events including the discovery of three bodies during the harvesting of lavender, its integration into police services, inter-border relations between the French villages and the Italian villages, his military involvement and the apos Organization of the village (shops, restaurants). The interview ends with questions of everyday life in Libre, such as village festivals, trade, religious practice and smuggling., French

creator: Michel (Mme) (informant), Santucci, Armande (informant), Bitton, Michele (investigator)
description: The interviewer interviewed two friends, both former retired nurses from Pertuis Hospital. She is essentially interested in the testimony of the first informant on the Resistance of her brother. The first informant shows personal records to the interviewer. During the Second World War, the informant lived in the Old Port of Marseilles while her mother and her brother moved to Pertuis where they had family. She then lived in the Rafle of Marseilles during which she was deported to the sorting camp of Frejus. On his return to Marseilles, all the dwellings had been destroyed. She decided to join her mother and her brother in Pertuis at the end of 1943. The brother of the informant was resistant to Pertuis and died as a resistant in an accident created by the Americans. Ten men died that day and families were warned during the day. The informant speaks about her funeral and the emotion created by this tragedy. The mother of the informant often tried to discourage her son from being involved in the Resistance. In 1944, the informant began working at the Pertuis hospital as a nurse. She then took part in the medical care of the victims of the La Simone explosion. She remembers that there were arrests of Pertuisians during the war, as well as assassinations. The investigator reads the testimony of Gaston Gilly on the Resistance of Ropdolphe Santucci, the brother of the informant. The informants talk about the allied bombing of the Americans in France, especially those of Marseilles. The first informant comments on photographs and documents about her brother and explains his life before he enters the Resistance, notably his trade as a plumber learned in apprenticeship. At the end of the interview, the two informants talk about their nursing work at the Pertuis hospital., French
